      {
         "text": "### The Peopling of Brazil\n\nIt is not unusual to talk with people and, when asking them *\"Who discovered Brazil?\"*, to receive the answer: *\"The Portuguese\"*. But how could the Portuguese have *\"discovered\"* it when there were already people here?\n\nAnother important issue is the traditional approach to history teaching, which frequently omits the existence of *Pindorama* (the Indigenous name for the Brazilian territory) (<htcite0>; <htcite1>). The conventional narrative only begins discussing this region when it becomes \"Brazil\".\n\nThis text seeks to recover the memory of Indigenous peoples by presenting their familial and social structures. We will also discuss racial mixing and attempt to reassess their Indigenous past (<htcite2>).",
         "source": [
            {
               "type": 1,
               "uuid": "01b6f0e8-66dc-4afb-b895-9dddd4a7c6dd",
               "text": "Farias, R.",
               "page": "pp. 1017",
               "date_time": {
                  "type": "gregory",
                  "year": "1997",
                  "month": "-1",
                  "day": "-1"
               }
            },
            {
               "type": 1,
               "uuid": "ffc2d22b-dfcc-4a5d-be17-d28c10d5d49f",
               "text": "Carrato, José F.",
               "page": "",
