      {
         "text": "#### The First Inhabitants\n\n**Figure 1** shows a map with territorial borders established over centuries, which differ significantly from the lands occupied by hunter-gatherer peoples. These groups moved seasonally, adapting to climate changes (<htcite0>).\n\nThe first inhabitants arrived around <htdate0> and remained in the region until <htdate1>. They did not practice agriculture nor use ceramics, living mainly along the coast, where they had abundant marine protein sources. The accumulation of shells and bones formed **sambaquis** (shell mounds) (<htcite1>; <htcite2>; <htcite3>).\n\nAnother key detail is their life expectancy, estimated at around 30 years (<htcite4>), which contrasts with European accounts from the early colonial period.\n\nAlthough they declined with the arrival of the Tupi-Guaraní, there is no evidence they went completely extinct; instead, they integrated with the newcomers (<htcite5>). Some researchers suggest the *Botocudos* may be their descendants (<htcite6>).",
         "source": [
            {
               "type": 1,
               "uuid": "e7ba42a9-953e-4225-b8ad-1076cb2cafdd",
               "text": "Lanata, José Luis",
