      {
         "text": "#### Tupi-Guarani\n\nBy <htdate0>, the Tupi-Guaraní—originating from the continent's interior—reached the coast, displacing earlier groups. Unlike their predecessors, they had ceramics, agriculture, and warfare techniques, using bows and arrows (<htcite0>; <htcite1>).\n\nIn the 500 years before colonization, these groups were mainly coastal. The Tupi, however, preferred the highlands, where the land was better for farming, only visiting the coast for fishing and rituals (<htcite2>).\n\nIt is also important to note the internal conflicts and territorial divisions that emerged with the Tupi-Guaraní migration. An emblematic example is the warfare between the Tupi and Carijós (<htcite3>).",
         "source": [
            {
               "type": 1,
               "uuid": "0505aae4-71b5-470f-8999-40e9bf943e3c",
               "text": "FERNANDES DE ANDRADE, W. T.",
