         "history": [
            {
               "text": "It is impossible to determine individual names when working with sambaquis. Therefore, denying their existence would be much worse. With this, we will present some individuals as \"unknown\".\n\nTheir presence in the Brazilian territory (*Pindorama*) is incontestable, with sambaquis found in different regions (<htcite0>). The mitochondrial DNA (mtDNA) collected in Thiago Ferraz da Silva’s research shows that individuals had haplogroups characteristic of the Americas (*Abya Yala*)—A2, B2, C1b, C1c, C1d, and D1—with a rare exception: C4c (<htcite1>).\n\nAs for the Y chromosome, the identified haplogroup was Q1b, the most common among Indigenous peoples of South America (*Abya Yala*) (<htcite2>).",
